Step 2: Create functions to clean the datasets & remove unwanted information

cleaner = function(dataset) {
  dataset = dataset %>%
    filter(SpatialDimension == "COUNTRY") %>%
    filter(TimeDimension == "YEAR") %>%
    filter(ParentLocation == "Americas" | ParentLocation == "Europe")
  
  #clean up the dataset
  dataset_c <- dataset[, !names(dataset) %in% 
                             c("DisaggregatingDimension1", "DisaggregatingDimension2", "DisaggregatingDimension3", 
                               "DisaggregatingDimension1ValueCode", "DisaggregatingDimension2ValueCode", "DisaggregatingDimension3ValueCode",
                               "DataSourceDimension", "DataSourceDimensionValueCode",
                               "Low", "High", "Comments",
                               "SpatialDimension", "SpatialDimensionCode","ParentLocationCode", 
                               "SpatialDimensionValueCode", "TimeDimensionValue",
                               "TimeDimensionBegin", "TimeDimensionEnd", "Date", "NumericValue", "Id", "TimeDimension")]
  
  dataset_c = dataset_c %>%
    arrange(desc(TimeDim))
  
  #rename the cols
  names(dataset_c) <- c("DiseaseCode", "Location", "Year", "PeopleSick")
  
  #turn the values in PeopleSick into ints
  dataset_c$PeopleSick <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(as.character(dataset_c$PeopleSick)))
  
  #multiple year entries into one entry per year
  combined_data <- dataset_c %>%
    group_by(Location, Year, DiseaseCode) %>%
    summarise(combined = sum(as.numeric(PeopleSick), na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")
}
grapher = function(clean_dataset, title) {
  ggplot(clean_dataset, aes(x = Year, y = combined, color = Location, group = Location)) +
    geom_line(size = 1) +  # Creates lines for each country
    labs(title = title, 
         x = "Year", 
         y = "Number of Diagnosed Cases") +  # Adds labels
    theme_grey()
  
}

# Add a DiseaseType column for each cleaned dataframe
clean_diptheria$DiseaseType <- "Diptheria"

# Combine all dataframes
all_diseases <- rbind(clean_diptheria, clean_con_rubella, clean_measles, clean_mumps, 
                      clean_neo_tenatus, clean_polio, clean_total_rubella, 
                      clean_total_tenatus, clean_yellow_fever)

# Modify the grapher function
grapher_all <- function(dataset, title) {
  ggplot(dataset, aes(x = Year, y = combined, color = DiseaseType, group = interaction(Location, DiseaseType))) +
    geom_line(size = 1) +
    labs(title = title, 
         x = "Year", 
         y = "Number of Diagnosed Cases") +
    theme_grey()
}

# Plot all diseases together
grapher_all(all_diseases, "Vaccine-Preventable Diseases Over Time")

A bit better, but the graph is too busy and we cant differentiate between the two locations. To kill two birds with one stone, we should divide it into two: America and Europe.

Step 5: Make a graph for each location

America Graph

#Make a sorting function for Americas
country_sorter = function(dataset, title) {
  new_dataset = dataset %>%
    filter(Location == "Americas")
  new_dataset$DiseaseCode = title
  return(new_dataset)
}

# Add a DiseaseType column for each cleaned dataframe
am_diptheria = country_sorter(clean_diptheria, "Diptheria")
am_con_rubella = country_sorter(clean_con_rubella, "Congenital Rubella Syndrome")
am_measles = country_sorter(clean_measles, "Measles")
am_mumps = country_sorter(clean_mumps, "Mumps")
am_neo_tenatus = country_sorter(clean_neo_tenatus, "Neonatal Tetanus")
am_polio = country_sorter(clean_polio, "Polio")
am_total_rubella = country_sorter(clean_total_rubella, "Total Rubella")
am_total_tenatus = country_sorter(clean_total_tenatus, "Total Tetanus")
am_yellow_fever = country_sorter(clean_yellow_fever, "Yellow Fever")

# Combine all dataframes
all_diseases <- rbind(am_diptheria, am_con_rubella, am_measles, am_mumps, am_neo_tenatus, am_polio, am_total_rubella, am_total_tenatus, am_yellow_fever)

#This graph is limited at 40,000 for the y value to better see the small changes over time. Just know that the Measles disease spiked to 65,000, and had an average of around 60,000 from 1985 to 1995.
grapher_all <- function(dataset, title) {
  ggplot(dataset, aes(x = Year, y = combined, color = DiseaseType, group = interaction(Location, DiseaseType))) +
    geom_line(size = 1) +
    ylim(0, 40000) +
    labs(title = title, 
         subtitle = "*y-value limited at 40,000 to better observe changes",
         x = "Year", 
         y = "Number of Diagnosed Cases") +
    theme_grey()
}

# Plot all diseases together
grapher_all(all_diseases, "Vaccine-Preventable Diseases Over Time in America")

Now we can really see the more subtle changes within each dataset.

Americas:

I can see 3 timeframes where majority (or at least half) of the diseases experience an some form of an uptick. In the 1980s, right before/during the year 2000, and possibly right before the 2020s. I cant see any areas where majority (or at least half) of the diseases experienced some form of downwards slope. The closest thing is when, from 1970 to 1995, where three (maybe four) diseases had a gradual negative slope.

Europe:

Honestly, I cant get much from this graph. There are only two or three diseases for each possible uptick shown, and the three main diseases that have any significant number of cases experience general volatility that makes it impossible to correlate with others. The one slight trend I can find is how, from 2005 to 2020, three diseases saw a gradual decrease in the height of the peaks experienced.

How do those trends relate to global events?

Im considering global events as possible explanations rather than events that just took place in the country as the world was (still is) so interconnected.

Upticks:

1980s - Fall of the Berlin Wall, AIDS epidemic, MTV was created 2000s - Hurricane Katrina, War on Terrorism 2018/20 - Humanitarian crises in Yemen & Venezuela, #MeToo Movement, Cilmate Change becomes a very big thing
